            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Ari Ben-Haim is a product of San Francisco\u2019s quieter side, born and raised in the fog-laced avenues of the Richmond District. His childhood home was a unique blend of cultures: his father, a secular Jewish intellectual who ran a dusty used bookstore, and his mother, a pragmatic and warm Filipina nurse. Ari grew up navigating the space between his father\u2019s philosophical debates and his mother\u2019s deep-rooted community values, a childhood scented with old paper and chicken adobo.\n\nThis duality defined his early adulthood. Wanting to channel his mother's compassion, he enrolled in the Social Work program at San Francisco State University in the late 90s. But the city's burgeoning nightlife and a hidden struggle with anxiety pulled him off course. He dropped out, falling into a decade-long spiral of addiction that cost him relationships and nearly his life. This period became his crucible. Hitting rock bottom in his late 30s, he finally sought help, finding salvation not in a formal program, but in the shared stories of others who had walked the same path.\n\nThis experience became his calling. Unable to return to a formal degree, he earned a certification as a Peer Support Specialist. Now, Ari channels his \"lived experience\" into his work at a non-profit serving at-risk youth. His past isn't a source of shame but a bridge of empathy, allowing him to connect with teens navigating the same systems that once failed him.\n\nHis daily life is a study in routine and gratitude. He lives in a small, rent-controlled apartment in the Inner Sunset, a short ride on the N-Judah from his office in the Tenderloin. His income is modest for the city, but it\u2019s enough. His social life is small but strong, built around a few close friends from his recovery journey. Ari\u2019s connection to San Francisco is profound; he has witnessed its transformation from a haven for eccentrics to a hub of tech wealth, and he works daily in the cracks where the city\u2019s most vulnerable fall. His dream isn't to get rich, but to stay sober, to watch the teens he mentors find their footing, and to one day afford a small condo in the city that both broke and saved him."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers being nine years old, sitting on a stack of books in his father\u2019s Richmond district shop. Dust motes danced in the light slanting through the foggy window. The air was thick with the scent of aging paper and binding glue. Then, the bell on the door would jingle and his mother would arrive after her hospital shift, a container of still-warm adobo in her hands. In that moment, he felt perfectly held between two worlds, believing love smelled like both old books and garlic soy sauce.\n\n2.\nThe decision came on a cold, grey afternoon at SF State, around 1999. He stood near the library, the weight of his social work textbooks feeling like an accusation in his backpack. A wave of anxiety, sharp and metallic, washed over him. He watched the M-Ocean View streetcar rattle past, heading downtown. In that instant, he knew he wouldn't go to class. He turned and walked away from the campus, not with relief, but with the terrifying, hollow freedom of a man severing his own lifeline.\n\n3.\nHis rock bottom wasn\u2019t a dramatic crash, but a silent Tuesday night in his late 30s. He was in a bare SRO room in the Tenderloin, watching the rain streak the grimy window. His phone buzzed\u2014a missed call from his mom, which he knew he couldn't answer. He caught his reflection in the dark glass: a hollowed-out stranger. The profound loneliness of that moment was absolute, a silence so complete it felt like an ending. It was the moment he realized he was utterly lost.\n\n4.\nThe turning point happened in a grim church basement, under the hum of fluorescent lights. He was clutching a styrofoam cup of terrible coffee, expecting nothing. Then a man, older and weathered, started sharing his story. The details were so painfully familiar\u2014the isolation, the lies, the shame\u2014that Ari felt a jolt, as if hearing his own secret thoughts spoken aloud. For the first time in a decade, the suffocating feeling of being unique in his failure lifted. He wasn't alone. That shared story was the first handhold he found.\n\n5.\nJust last month, a teenager sat across from him in his small Tenderloin office, silent and guarded. After ten minutes of getting nowhere, Ari took a breath. \"When I was your age, my anxiety made it feel like my bones were vibrating,\" he said softly. The boy\u2019s head snapped up, his eyes wide with a flicker of recognition. That split-second of connection\u2014seeing his own past pain become a bridge to someone else\u2014filled Ari with a quiet, fierce gratitude. It made every hard day worth it."
